post_text: A change to the Operations Plan was voted on Friday morning at a School Board meeting. This change is reflective of the City of Fishers Risk Rating System and their guidance for schools. post_text:
The information below has been sent via Skylert:
4.2.20 - This afternoon, it was announced by Governor Eric Holcomb and State Superintendent Jennifer McCormick that all schools will remain closed through the end of the school year. This means that students and staff will not return to their classrooms and/or schools, and instruction will continue via eLearning. The last official day of school is Friday, May 22. We know this may come as a disappointment to many of our students, especially our seniors. We are working on alternative plans for commencement and will keep you updated. In addition, please continue to check our COVID-19 webpage and Frequently Asked Questions section for new information. Thank you for your continued support and patience as we work together to keep our community safe and healthy during this unprecedented crisis.

post_text: SOUND ON: During this time of isolation, there seems to be one thing that many people are turning to, and that is the arts. FHS Performing Arts Teacher Tess Tazioli has received messages from students daily saying how much they miss singing together as a choir; it is not only something they miss, but something they need, a way for them to feel connected and so much more. So she decided to spend an eLearning day with her students compiling this virtual choir arrangement. The song, Free at Last/Flight, is from their show choir set, a piece they were never able to sing at Show Choir State because of it being cancelled due to Covid-19. But where there is darkness, music will always be a candle.

Again, thank you for your support as we all work together to do what is best for our school community during this unprecedented health crisis.

OFFICIAL MESSAGE: In light of Governor Eric Holcomb‚Äôs request to slow the spread of COVID-19, Hamilton Southeastern Schools will close for students starting Monday, March 16 through Thursday, April 2. We will use a combination of eLearning and waiver days granted by Holcomb.

Students will be in school tomorrow, March 13 for a regular school day in which the teachers will prepare them for an extended time away. All buildings will close no later than 6 p.m.

We recognize how challenging this situation is for some of our families, students and staff. This decision was made after consultation with Hamilton County health officials and other Hamilton County schools.

We are finalizing plans to support our families during the closure and will communicate more information in the coming days.

Thank you for your support as we all work together to do what is best for our students, staff and families during this unprecedented health crisis.

post_text:
Sending congratulations to Rob Seymour, Athletic Director at Fishers High School! He has been recognized as a Certified Master Athletic Administrator by The National Interscholastic Athletic Administrators Association (NIAAA).

To earn this distinction, Rob has demonstrated exemplary knowledge, contributions and on-going professional development in the field of interscholastic athletic administration. The voluntary certification process included a thorough evaluation of the candidate's educational background, experience, NIAAA Leadership Courses and professional contributions. It is culminated with a practical written or oral presentation project. Rob is one of a very elite group of interscholastic athletic administrators nationwide to attain this level of professionalism. Thank you for your leadership, Mr. Seymour! üëèü§©

The results of the school start time survey are now posted online. For reference, this was an open-ended questionnaire asking for input on changing the start times for our schools. It was available for parents and community members to fill-out between 11/20/19 - 12/20/19. We received 1,840 comments in total. Each comment was read and tallied. We appreciate your thoughts on this matter. Please know the school start times and three-tier transportation proposal are two separate issues. No decision has been made on either.

https://www.hseschools.org/happenings/school-start-time

post_text: As follow-up to the Indiana American Water issue, we wanted thank all of our concerned parents for their calls and emails. To reiterate, Harrison Parkway Elementary is the only school affected. Staff and students at HPE are currently using bottled water and we hope the issue will be resolved soon. As information, DES is on a well and all of our other HSE Schools utilize Citizens Water. There are adjacent neighborhoods that are on Indiana American Water so it can be confusing! We've learned a lot more about our water systems this AM. üòä

post_text: Just a heads up for any Harrison Parkway family: school will be on regular schedule tomorrow, 1/14, despite being under a boil water advisory issued by Indiana American Water. Consistent with previous water quality issues, bottled water will be supplied for drinking and all water fountains will be shut off. Food Services will also follow safety protocols. HPE families should have received a Skylert stating the information above. Harrison Parkway Elementary PTO

post_text:
Tis the season‚Ä¶

A kindergarten and a first grade class have paired up this year as BUDDIES and are working on various projects.

One lesson centered around empathy and how to plant kindness. After a guest speaker shared about the need some of our families experience this time of year, the two classes decided to do something to help. Since they are all toy experts, the students unpacked and sorted toys at the Hamilton County Fairgrounds earlier this month that will go out to 8,000 Hoosier families in need for the holidays.

The teachers, Mrs. Lacy (Kindergarten) and Mrs. Torzewski (Third Grade) said this about the experience: ‚ÄúWe can be leaders in our school and now we want to show them they can also be leaders within their community.‚Äù Lantern Road Elementary School

post_text: Thank you Duke Energy! Hamilton Southeastern Schools was the recipient of $103,246 in rebates through Duke's Smart Saver Business Lighting Rebate Program. We recently upgraded more than 5,700 lighting fixtures at Sand Creek Elementary, Sand Creek Intermediate and Hamilton Southeastern Intermediate Junior High with new energy efficient LEDs fixtures. We're proud to say this project has translated into considerable energy and cost savings for the district. üí°üí°üí°
